SIMPLE: restitution
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Restitution
<hw>Res`ti*tu"tion</hw> <pr>(r?s`t?*t?"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>restitution</ets>, L. <ets>restitutio</ets>. See
<er>Restitute</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
restoring anything to its rightful owner, or of making good, or of
giving an equivalent for any loss, damage, or injury;
indemnification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>restitution</qex> of ancient rights unto the crown.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>restitution</qex> to the value makes.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is offered or given in return for what
has been lost, injured, or destroyed; compensation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The act of returning to, or
recovering, a former state; <as>as, the <ex>restitution</ex> of an
elastic body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The movement of rotation which
usually occurs in childbirth after the head has been delivered, and
which causes the latter to point towards the side to which it was
directed at the beginning of labor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Restoration; return; indemnification; reparation;
compensation; amends; remuneration.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Restitutor</ent>⟦br⟧
